From d051331d6209b4c0a45e1bbb1798f712da3cc8c1 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Gravio <gravio@uni-muenster.de>
Date: Wed, 29 Apr 2026 23:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] cython POC: port framewise_inside_polygon_roi to Cython
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Proof of concept for replacing numba kernels with ahead-of-time-
compiled Cython. Adds a single ported kernel
(framewise_inside_polygon_roi) alongside the existing numba
version — additive, not replacing.

Why this kernel as POC:
- Self-contained (only reads bp_location and roi_coords arrays)
- Branch-heavy ray-casting algorithm — exactly the shape where
  AOT compilation can beat numba JIT
- Small (~20 lines) — easy to fully understand and review
- Returns boolean output that's easy to byte-verify against
  the numba version

What's NOT in this patch:
- The kernel chain (feature_subset_kernels.py) is unchanged —
  it still calls the numba version via FeatureExtractionMixin.
- Production behavior is unchanged. The Cython kernel exists
  but is unreachable from the feature extraction pipeline
  until the user runs the verification on their workstation
  and we wire it up in a follow-up.

What changed:

1. NEW: mufasa/_native/__init__.py
   Package init for the new mufasa._native sub-package.
   Documents the rationale for AOT compilation (libgomp removal,
   no JIT warm-up, cleaner debugging).

2. NEW: mufasa/_native/inside_polygon.pyx
   Cython port of FeatureExtractionMixin.framewise_inside_polygon_roi.
   - Same algorithm (ray casting, j % n_poly indexing, etc.)
   - Same input/output contract
   - Compiler directives: language_level=3, boundscheck=False,
     wraparound=False, cdivision=True, initializedcheck=False
   - Internally coerces to float64 for byte-equivalence with
     the numba version
   - Inner loops use Cython typed memoryviews — no Python
     overhead per iteration

3. NEW: setup.py
   Minimal shim that compiles the Cython extension at install
   time. The bulk of package config remains in pyproject.toml.
   - extra_compile_args=["-O3", "-Wall"]
   - -ffast-math intentionally NOT enabled (would reorder FP
     ops and break byte-equivalence)
   - numpy include path added via np.get_include()

4. MODIFIED: pyproject.toml
   [build-system].requires now includes:
   - Cython>=3.0
   - numpy>=1.24
   So `pip install -e .` triggers Cython compilation. Without
   these in build deps, the build fails before setup.py runs
   with "No module named Cython.Build".

5. NEW: tests/smoke_cython_poc_structure.py — 8 cases:
   - .pyx exists with required compiler directives
   - kernel function name matches what it replaces
   - ray-casting algorithm structure preserved (outer/inner
     loops, j % n_poly indexing, inside flip)
   - mufasa/_native/__init__.py exists
   - setup.py declares the extension correctly with numpy
     include path, -O3, no -ffast-math in extra_compile_args
   - pyproject.toml [build-system] requires Cython + numpy
   - existing numba kernel still in place (POC is additive)
   - feature_subset_kernels.py still calls numba version
     (POC is unreachable from production until validated)

6. NEW: tests/smoke_native_inside_polygon.py
   User-runnable on workstation (NOT sandbox-runnable).
   Generates synthetic polygon + body-part data at multiple
   scales, calls both numba and Cython implementations, and:
   - Verifies byte-equivalence (np.array_equal)
   - Times both with discarded warm-up runs
   - Reports speedup
   Pass criteria: byte-equivalent + within 2× of numba.

USER ACTIONS REQUIRED:

1. Apply the patch + reinstall:
     pip install -e .
   (this is when Cython compilation happens; takes ~30 seconds)

2. Run the workstation test:
     python tests/smoke_native_inside_polygon.py

3. Read the output:
   - "Byte-equivalence: PASS" + speedup ≥ 1.0×
     → Cython POC validates. Worth porting more kernels.
   - "Byte-equivalence: PASS" + speedup < 0.5×
     → Cython is slower than numba JIT. POC fails the
       performance bar. Either the kernel doesn't benefit
       from AOT (likely true for memory-bound kernels) or
       the .pyx needs tuning.
   - "Byte-equivalence: FAIL" → the .pyx has a logic bug.
     Investigate the diff before doing anything else.

If the POC validates, follow-ups would:
- Port the other ROI test kernels (rectangle, circle)
- Port jitted_hull (the convex-hull kernel)
- Decide whether to remove numba from feature_subsets entirely
  (would let _run_parallel switch back from spawn to fork —
  faster worker startup)
- Wire the Cython kernels into feature_subset_kernels.py to
  actually use them in production

If the POC fails: this patch can be reverted cleanly. Nothing
in production changed.

Verified in sandbox:
- All 18 smoke tests pass
- AST audit reports zero errors
- The Cython source files compile-check clean to Python's
  parser (the .pyx is invalid Python so we don't py_compile it,
  but its structure is verified by the structure test)

Cannot be verified in sandbox:
- That Cython actually compiles the .pyx (no compiler)
- Performance numbers (need real workload)
- Byte-equivalence at runtime (need both kernels imported)

Stack now at 48 patches:
  46. mufasa_launcher           (smart workbench launcher)
  47. parallel_spawn_context    (spawn fix for OpenMP-fork)
  48. cython_inside_polygon_poc (this patch)
